* Nenbutsu-ji was founded in Genna 8 (1622) at the order of {{ill|Matsudaira Tadayoshi|ja|松平定勝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsudaira Tadayoshi|qq=}}, a half-brother of {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Ieyasu|qq=}}. The temple’s founder was the monk {{ill|Fukushū|ja|袋中|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukushū|qq=}}.<ref>[https://narakanko-enjoy.com/?p=11497 "Nenbutsu-ji: A Temple Linked to Ieyasu, Just Steps from Kintetsu Nara Station"]</ref>
* According to folklore, Tokugawa Ieyasu, pursued by {{ill|Sanada Yukimura|ja|真田信繁|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanada Yukimura|qq=}} during the {{ill|Winter Campaign of the Siege of Osaka|ja|大坂冬の陣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Winter Campaign of the Siege of Osaka|qq=}}, hid inside a coffin at a cooper’s shop on the temple grounds to escape. While this tale is not confirmed, skirmishes between Ieyasu and Sanada’s forces near Kizu are recorded in the {{ill|Tokugawa Jikki|ja|徳川実紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Jikki|qq=}}. A similar story is associated with {{ill|Saijō-ji (Nara)|ja|西照寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saijō-ji (Nara)|qq=}} in Nara.
* Fukushū’s disciple, Zenbiki, found a unique [[Amida Nyorai]] mandala in a shop in Nara while searching for the {{ill|Taima Mandala|ja|当麻曼荼羅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taima Mandala|qq=}}. This mandala, known as the ''Chikō Mandala,'' became a focal point for Fukushū, who settled at what was then called ''Kōbōzan'' to establish the temple. Early records refer to the site as ''Mimokuzan,'' and the temple’s original image of worship was a painted depiction of the {{ill|Zenkōji Amida Triad|ja|善光寺式阿弥陀三尊|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenkōji Amida Triad|qq=}}.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Yasuhiko Inagaki|date=March 2020|title=Annotated and Republished: "History of Gōmazan Zenkō-ji" by Ryōjō (Fukushū)|journal=Bunkyo University Kokubun|volume=49|pages=11–48|url=http://id.nii.ac.jp/1351/00007618/}}</ref>
* During the Kan’ei era (1624–1644), Fukushū collected and transcribed a complete set of Buddhist scriptures, which were stored in the temple’s sutra repository. These scriptures were scattered by the late Edo period.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Tetsusei Miyake|date=2008|title=The History and Current Status of Fukushū’s Complete Buddhist Scripture Collection|journal=Kokusai Bukkyōgaku Daigakuin Daigaku Kiyō|volume=12|pages=27–56|url=http://id.nii.ac.jp/1153/00000045/}}</ref>
* In 1862 (Bunkyū 2), the sutra repository and cemetery were relocated during restoration efforts for the nearby {{ill|Emperor Kaika Mausoleum|ja|開化天皇陵|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Kaika Mausoleum|qq=}}. The temple declined during the late Edo and early Meiji periods but was later revived under new leadership.

== Features ==

* Wooden standing statue of {{ill|Amida Nyorai|ja|阿弥陀如来|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amida Nyorai|qq=}} (Kamakura period)
* Stone statue of {{ill|Jizō Bosatsu|ja|地蔵菩薩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jizō Bosatsu|qq=}} (Muromachi period)
* Memorial to {{ill|Matsudaira Tadayoshi|ja|松平定勝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsudaira Tadayoshi|qq=}}
* Grave of Kyūzan Motoyasu, magistrate of Nara
* Rokujimyōgō stele by Jion
* Graves of the {{ill|Konparu Family|ja|金春家|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konparu Family|qq=}}

== Access ==
* 2 minutes on foot from Exit 7-S, {{ill|Kintetsu Nara Station|ja|近鉄奈良駅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kintetsu Nara Station|qq=}} ({{OSM Directions|start=34.68416,135.82587|goal=34.68360,135.82464|name=Route Guide}})
* 4 minutes on foot from "Kintetsu Nara Station" stop on the {{ill|Nara Kōtsū|ja|奈良交通|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara Kōtsū|qq=}} City Loop (Outer Circle) bus line ({{OSM Directions|start=34.68449,135.82717|goal=34.68360,135.82464|name=Route Guide}})
* 10 minutes on foot from the east exit of {{ill|JR Nara Station|ja|奈良駅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JR Nara Station|qq=}} ({{OSM Directions|start=34.68113,135.81943|goal=34.68360,135.82464|name=Route Guide}})

