|author=Yasuhiko Inagaki|date=March 2020|title=Annotated and Republished: "History of Gōmazan Zenkō-ji" by Ryōjō (Fukushū)|journal=Bunkyo University Kokubun|volume=49|pages=11–48|url=http://id.nii.ac.jp/1351/00007618/}}</ref> * During the Kan’ei era (1624–1644), Fukushū collected and transcribed a complete set of Buddhist scriptures, which were stored in the temple’s sutra repository. These scriptures were scattered by the late Edo period.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Tetsusei Miyake|date=2008|title=The History and Current Status of Fukushū’s Complete Buddhist Scripture Collection|journal=Kokusai Bukkyōgaku Daigakuin Daigaku Kiyō|volume=12|pages=27–56|url=http://id.nii.ac.jp/1153/00000045/}}</ref> * In 1862 (Bunkyū 2), the sutra repository and cemetery were relocated during restoration efforts for the nearby {{ill|Emperor Kaika Mausoleum|ja|開化天皇陵|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Kaika Mausoleum|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 開化天皇|1=Emperor Kaika|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q333548}}. The temple declined during the late Edo and early Meiji periods but was later revived under new leadership.
== Features ==
* Wooden standing statue of [[:en:Amitābha|Amida Nyorai]] (Kamakura period) * Stone statue of [[:en:Kṣitigarbha|Jizō Bosatsu]] (Muromachi period) * Memorial to [[:en:Hisamatsu Sadakatsu|Matsudaira Tadayoshi]] * Grave of Kyūzan Motoyasu, magistrate of Nara * Rokujimyōgō stele by Jion * Graves of the {{ill|Konparu Family|ja|金春家|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konparu Family|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 金春流|1=Konparu|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q4525036}}
== Access == * 2 minutes on foot from Exit 7-S, [[:en:Kintetsu Nara Station|Kintetsu Nara Station]]
* 4 minutes on foot from "Kintetsu Nara Station" stop on the [[:en:Nara Kotsu Bus Lines|Nara Kōtsū]] City Loop (Outer Circle) bus line
* 10 minutes on foot from the east exit of [[:en:Nara Station|JR Nara Station]] == References == {{Reflist|2}} == See Also == {{Commonscat}}
